{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
The parties may choose to reach settlement after the evidentiary portion of trial ends but before the judge or jury renders a decision. A settlement at this time may be desirable where both parties are concerned about the case\rquote s outcome. For example, a party may want to settle if it appears the judge may misapply the law, or the jury appears confused about the facts or how to apply the law. These circumstances may make an appeal (and the associated costs) inevitable and unattractive. A settlement at this point may be especially desirable if trial went poorly for one party who wants to avoid an unfavorable judgment and the publicity associated with it.
\par 
}
}
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
\u160\'3f
\par 
}
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ri0 \i0 \qj \fs18 \li0 
{\b0 \cf19 \f0 \ul0 \strike0 \i0 \fs18 \sa0 \sb0 
